comment.author: 51979177@N02
comment._content: Ah! Some low hanging fruit, kindly left by 'you-know-who'...per various digitised newspaper hits, Thompson & Flemming (clothing importers) appear to have traded at 5 Wynyard St from ca. 1880...they appear to have moved to 1 Wynyard St in the later part of 1883...I gather that's where we see their signs in this pic...One of the two Flemming partners quit the firm in 1885...the remaining partners continued to trade as Thompson and Flemming...the firm became insolvent by ca. May 1887 nla.gov.au/nla.news-article98467770 ...after which I can't find any reference to T&F as current occupants of 1 Wynyard St...by May 1888, 1 Wynyard St was being advertised for lease... J. [Jabez] Mather & Co (woollens warehousemen, cnr York & Wynyard Sts) also hit the skids at about this time...their estate had been assigned by early March 1887 (notice column 1) nla.gov.au/nla.news-article13628894 ...I can't find any references to J. Mather & Co as current occupants at York & Wynyard Sts beyond this time either. So far, all up I'd say we're looking at a date range from ca. January-February-March 1886 (scaffolding removed from the GPO tower) to ca. mid 1887 or possibly into 1888 (how long do former tenant's signs stay up?).
